Suppose that the Federal Reserve (Fed) decided to implement a policy where it would raise the interest rate by 0.25%. If the initial interest rate is 1.5%, how would this policy affect the money supply?

The money supply will increase. When the Fed raises the interest rate, it makes borrowing more expensive, which reduces the amount of money people are willing to borrow. This decrease in demand for money leads to a reduction in the money supply.

In a hospital study, 139 patients were randomly assigned to an intervention group or a control group. The intervention group received two weekly sessions of physical exercise, while the control group did not. At the end of the two weeks, 66 people in the intervention group and 63 people in the control group showed improvement. Is there sufficient evidence to conclude that the intervention was effective in improving the quality of patients' lives at the 1% significance level? Explain your reasoning.

Given information:

{eq}\begin{align*}

n &= 139\\

{n_1} &= 66\\

{n_2} &= 63

\end{align*}

{/eq}



Null hypothesis: There is no significant difference between the intervention and control groups.

{eq}{H_0}:{\mu _1} = {\mu _2}

{/eq}



Alternative hypothesis: There is a significant difference between the intervention and control groups.

{eq}{H_1}:{\mu _1} \ne {\mu _2}

{/eq}



The proportion of intervention group showing improvement is:

{eq}\begin{align*}

{{\hat p}_1} &= \dfrac{{{n_1}}}{{{n_1} + {n_2}}}\\

&= \dfrac{{66}}{{139}}\\

&= 0.475

\end{align*}

{/eq}



The proportion of control group showing improvement is:

{eq}\begin{align*}

{{\hat p}_2} &= \dfrac{{{n_2}}}{{{n_1} + {n_2}}}\\

&= \dfrac{{63}}{{139}}\\

&= 0.453

\end{align*}

{/eq}



The pooled proportion of both groups is:

{eq}\begin{align*}

\hat p &= \dfrac{{{n_1} + {n_2}}}{{2 \times \left( {{n_1} + {n_2}} \right)}}\\

&= \dfrac{{139}}{{2 \times 139}}\\

&= 0.5

\end{align*}

{/eq}



The test statistic is:

{eq}\begin{align*}

t &= \dfrac{{{{\hat p}_1} - {{\hat p}_2}}}{{\sqrt {\hat p\left( {1 - \hat p} \right)\left( {\dfrac{1}{{{n_1}}} + \dfrac{1}{{{n_2}}}} \right)} }}\\

&= \dfrac{{0.475 - 0.453}}{{\sqrt {0.5\left( {1 - 0.5} \right)\left( {\dfrac{1}{{66}} + \dfrac{1}{{63}}} \right)} }}\\

&= 0.492

\end{align*}

{/eq}



The degree of freedom is:

{eq}\begin{align*}

df &= \left( {{n_1} - 1} \right) + \left( {{n_2} - 1} \right)\\

&= 65 + 62\\

&= 127

\end{align*}

{/eq}



The critical value at 1% level of significance from the t-table is:

{eq}{t_{\alpha /2}} = {t_{0.005}}

{/eq}

Since the degrees of freedom is greater than 10, we can use the normal distribution instead of t-distribution. The critical value at 1% level of significance from the standard normal table is:

{eq}{Z_{\alpha /2}} = {Z_{0.005}} = 2.576

{/eq}



Since the test statistic value is less than the critical value, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Therefore, there is not sufficient evidence to conclude that the intervention was effective in improving the quality of patients' lives at the 1% significance level.

