To find the sum of $\frac{1}{2}$ and $\frac{1}{3}$, we need to add them together. 

\begin{align*}
\text{Sum} &= \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \\
&= \frac{3}{6} + \frac{2}{6} \\
&= \frac{5}{6}
\end{align*}

To find the product of $\frac{1}{2}$ and $\frac{1}{3}$, we need to multiply them together.

\begin{align*}
\text{Product} &= \frac{1}{2} \times \frac{1}{3} \\
&= \frac{1}{6}
\end{align*}

To find the positive difference between the sum and the product, we subtract the product from the sum.

\begin{align*}
\text{Difference} &= \text{Sum} - \text{Product} \\
&= \frac{5}{6} - \frac{1}{6} \\
&= \frac{4}{6} \\
&= \frac{2}{3}
\end{align*}

<answer> $\frac{2}{3}$ </answer>

